It means the image has 'alt text' or an image description. This means that blind people can access a description of the photo.

It's really easy to add alt text to your images on twitter. This thread explains how! ⬇️👩‍🦯📲 https://t.co/ZalLHiqo4h
Name: Khushi 👩🏼‍🦯

Text:
RT @BlondeHistorian : It's easy to add alt text when you post an image on twitter.

In browser use the clickable 'add description link' or find 'alt' in the edit tab. 

Or on mobile you can find it in the 'edit' button options.

Here are the instructions for each device https://t.co/tuNhtRgblS
Name: Khushi 👩🏼‍🦯

Text:
RT @BlondeHistorian : My alt text top tips:

1. If there is text, include it.

2. What stands out to you in the image? A red coat? A skyscraper? A dog? Describe it!

3. Think about context. If it’s a fashion picture tell me about the clothes. If it’s a group photo I don’t need every outfit described. https://t.co/f8XcK1tgNR

looking back i loved those days in primary. i'd have my book and ma'am would ask me to read.. just like everyone else.
Name: Khushi 👩🏼‍🦯

Text:
i also learnt that we (Indian Braille users) are missing out on a lot.
many people think Braille has no use today.
but I miss it. I miss the comfort of taking the book under the blanket though it was a little heavy and reading.
i miss writing..
Name: Khushi 👩🏼‍🦯

Text:
i was and still am highly disappointed that India isn't a part of it.
if we'd have been a part of ICEB, we'd have gotten the help we need to completely switch to UEB.
i learnt about UEB too. would love to learn it someday.

Text:
after that I again didn't touch it.
i'd love to go back to it. to refresh my skills. to learn contracted (grade 2) Braille.
in 2019 or 2020 i don't remember what it was i learnt about ICEB.
and subscribed to their newsletter.

Text:

i still have those formulas written them.
i also realised that i loved it. contrary to what i thought, i missed my fingers sliding through those dots.
looking back i probably became nostalgic.
i still have 1 Perkins. i'll always have it.

Text:
I didn't know that I'd come to miss it so much. after class 8 (2016) I didn't touch Braille. at all.
in 2018 I decided to take out my Perkins and wrote formulas for physics and chemistry because thought I'd be able to learn them via Braille quicker.
